<br>
As a wizard who has been playing for over a year now, I've seen the issues raised by the increased damage output and haste items that have been added to the game.  I am sure you have thought of this already, but in case you have not, I've come up with a way out of the trap of needing increased hit points on mobs in order to balance against all the items that have forced you to increase the number of hit points the mobs have.<br>
<br>
First, my thoughts on the problem so that you see where I am comming from, then my solution to the problem:<br>
<br>
In old Norrath(pre-Kunark):<br>
Melees would do XX damage/second with weak/normal/best equipment.<br>
Casters would do YY damage/second with the available spells(all casters were expected to have the best spells available at their level), and with weak/normal/best equipment.<br>
<br>
With these pieces of knowledge, mobs and encounters could be balanced against groups of players, and in general, all classes should be roughly able to be functional, and desired in groups.<br>
<br>
With Kunark, Melees had their damage/second increased, both through better items, and haste effects being more the norm than the exception.  The weak items now are considered the normal before, and normal items are now equal or even better than the best equipment before the expansion.  Caster damage was increased slightly, with casting times reduced on level 51+ spells, but the damage increase/second for casters in the BEST situation did not measure up to the increase melee classes got.  On top of this, since melee items can be given to lower level characters, over time you find that formerly balanced encounters are now too easy based on availability of this new equipment.  As time goes on, items that are better than the best equipment in &quot;Old Norrath&quot;, make their way into the hands of level 20 characters, which throws off the balance of the entire game.<br>
<br>
This continued, until Velious.  Velious continued providing better and better melee equipment, no damage increases of any kind were given to the casting classes with new spells, and even the items provided, except for the Flowing Thoughts items did very little to improve the damage output of casters.  In order to compensate for the new equipment this time, the hit point cap is removed, the mobs do MUCH higher levels of damage, and this is to compensate for boosting the melee abilities beyond where the initial balance was intended to be.  In all cases now, the BEST damage output of melee classes per second has been boosted past the BEST damage output of the spellcasting classes.  Level 60 spells are added for wizards, and nothing to help those who are not yet level 60.  And so, the players complain.  <br>
<br>
That concludes my summary of what happened, and I believe you will agree that on the outside, the only way to help would be to increase the damage output from casters, or increase mana regeneration to regain the role of damage dealing classes.  I've come up with a better idea, and one that I believe you may find can be done without a complete redesign of the game.<br>
<br>
My idea is that if you increase the armor class of the mobs, you will reduce the ability of melees to do damage without reducing the ability of spell casters from doing damage.  By being careful with how much, even the twinked characters will have their ability to do damage reduced to where you want them to be, while boosting the benefit that casters bring to a group.  To balance this out, the hit points on mobs could be reduced in such a way that all characters will once again be balanced, and at the same time, without a &quot;nerf&quot;.  The issue in the past as I understand it, is that nerfs are considered bad, people complain when mob hit points and damage output is increased, and you wish to avoid that.  You can get a similar effect to this, without any need to say anything, by doing this armor class increase on the mobs, and at the same time, lowering the hit points of the mobs that have been boosted in order to combat the insane damage output.<br>
<br>
Thank you for your time.<br>
<br>
